Looks like a little drama happened here a couple days ago. It seems this fisher came across a squirrel and gave chase. The fisher made two tight loops in the scrub on the south side of the trail as the squirrel cut back and forth (sorry, no photos of this). The squirrel then ran across the trail toward the fenced enclodure with the fisher following. The fisher's 2x2 bounding strides measured 35", 38", 36", 35". The squrrel's bounds were longer than my mini-tape measure could reach--somewhere around 7'. The squirrel lept through one of the 3"x6" openings in the fence, and the fisher followed. I lost the squirrel trail and the fisher trail continued in a pretty straight line for at least 20' until the terrain obscured my view. I'll post clearer photos if I have any.

An old red fox scat next to the even older remains of a deer carcass. The deer died last winter and had a trail camera on it for several weeks recording scavenging by fox as well as fisher, raven, crow, and other birds.

This was an interesting scene. A whitetail had been struck by a car and was lying in the ditch. Red fox were scavenging the carcass (based on surrounding tracks and scat), but were only entering through the back and rump, not the abdomen. I'm guessing that the fox were feeding on the back in order to keep more-or-less out of the line of sight of the road--using the carcass as cover. I've never seen this feeding pattern before. To test our hypothesis, we rolled the carcass over so the legs were facing away from the road. We'll head back in a few days to see if the fox (or others) open up the abdomen.

When I saw these in the field, I was sure they were deer mouse tracks. As I look at the photos again, the tracks appear more elongated than deer mouse, and there seems to be more difference in size between front and hind than I would expect. Might these be house mouse tracks instead? They were found about 100m from a cabin that is currently unoccupied.

This is the first time I have ever successfully trailed a frog--if you can call it that. We picked up this very fresh trail as we were walking back to our cars after a morning of tracking. We had walked this road only a little over an hour earlier. Very strangely, both the individual tracks and the stride length were getting smaller the longer we followed the trail--enough so that we checked several times to make sure it was indeed a single continuous trail. When we "caught up" to the animal, the answer to our puzzle was revealed. This poor frog was drying out and shriveling up as it hopped! we're not really sure why it left the pond in the first place.
I'm guessing a chorus frog or spring peeper, based on the size.
Another unexpected otter observation. We were surprised to see tracks in this spot--not very close to the waterways and apparently heading away from them. Perhaps this is a dispersing juvenile?

Running deer. The track pattern appeared to show a transition from a transverse gallop to a running pace. I have not recorded a running pace in a deer before. I presume that this is a transitional gait between a gallop and a walk.

These are either robin tracks or mourning dove tracks. When I saw these in the field, I presumed they were mourning dove, based in large part on the habitat and the long trail of fairly short steps. My colleague later IDed them as robin, looking primarily at the individual tracks. Looking back at my photos, I'm leaning toward robin as well. The step length is about 3", which is shorter than what Elbroch lists for robin running or skipping trails. But the track proportions appear to be a better match for robin than dove--so I'm going with that for now and welcome correction.

I'm pretty confident these are tracks of an Icterid. Based on the size, location, and behavior, I think cowbird is the most likely candidate, but they fall in the size range for red-singed blackbird as well.

I suspect this is the trail of a garter snake. We observed one moving across the road a little ways up the road from here shortly before finding this trail. The other likely candidate is a fox snake (also seen nearby). Other snakes in the area are either too small (smooth greensnake, red-bellied snake) or leave very different looking trails (bullsnake, hognose).

A puzzling canid trail. These tracks are unusually large and robust for coyote, but surprisingly small and delicate for wolf. The most unusual feature of the trail is the stride length -- 140 to 160cm (55" - 63" same foot to same foot). The only canid I have ever measured trotting strides that long for is a wolf. I would not be surprised if a few long-legged dog breeds could leave strides that long, but the track morphology isn't a match for any of the large breeds I am familiar with. Greyhounds are hare-footed; Malamutes and Great Danes are cat-footed. Domestic dogs are uncommon (and prohibited) on the property, but show up form time to time. The animal's behavior, track pattern and foot morphology were all more typical of a wild canid. This is a bit of a mystery for now--and may be associated with the mysterious canine scat we found nearby this summer:
